_Split out from #102 (one issue per bug). Found via an AI-assisted code review with manual verification against commit `5f8ce875`._

Workers unconditionally push their run-data into a static pool at every run end, but the master only drains that pool when `need_a_run_streamer` is true. When no run-mode digitizer is configured, the pool is never cleared and accumulates stale objects that get merged into later runs.

**Affected files**
- `gemc/actions/run/gRunAction.cc:174-179` (`EndOfRunAction`: workers always `stash_worker_run_data()`)
- `gemc/actions/run/gRunAction.cc:181-184` (master drains via `take_completed_worker_run_data()` only inside `if (IsMaster() && need_a_run_streamer)`)
- `gemc/actions/run/gRunAction.cc:251-268` (`stash_worker_run_data` / `take_completed_worker_run_data`)

**Details**
Every worker stashes at the end of every run, regardless of streamer configuration:

```cpp
// Worker threads do not publish merged run data. Instead, they hand their
// completed run-level accumulation to the shared pool and return.
if (!IsMaster()) {
    stash_worker_run_data();
    return;
}
```

But the only consumer that drains the static pool is gated on `need_a_run_streamer`:

```cpp
if (IsMaster() && need_a_run_streamer) {
    auto completed_run_data = take_completed_worker_run_data();   // the only drain
    ...
}
```

`take_completed_worker_run_data()` is what moves-out and clears `completed_worker_run_data`:

```cpp
auto result = std::move(completed_worker_run_data);
completed_worker_run_data.clear();
return result;
```

When `need_a_run_streamer == false` (no run-mode digitizer this run), workers still stash but the master never takes. The static `completed_worker_run_data` keeps growing run after run. If a later run *does* enable a run streamer, `take_completed_worker_run_data()` returns this run's contributions **plus** all the stale ones from prior runs, and the merge loop folds them all into `merged_run_data` — double-counting `events_processed` and any run-summary counters.

**Impact**
Run-level summaries become wrong whenever run-streamer need varies across runs (stale prior-run data merged in), and the static pool leaks memory across runs even in the common no-run-streamer case. Correctness bug for normalized run observables (`events_processed` is the normalization denominator in `normalize_run_data`).

**Proposed fix**
Only stash when the master will actually drain — i.e., gate the worker stash on `need_a_run_streamer`, the same condition the master uses. This keeps the pool empty by construction when no run streamer exists, and avoids stale merges.

```diff
 	// Worker threads do not publish merged run data. Instead, they hand their
 	// completed run-level accumulation to the shared pool and return.
 	if (!IsMaster()) {
-		stash_worker_run_data();
+		// Only contribute to the master merge pool when a run-mode streamer will drain it;
+		// otherwise the pool is never taken and would accumulate stale prior-run data.
+		if (need_a_run_streamer) { stash_worker_run_data(); }
 		return;
 	}
```

This is correct and idempotent: workers and master agree on `need_a_run_streamer` (both compute it in `BeginOfRunAction` from the same digitization map for the same run), so the pool is filled iff it will be drained that run.

**Alternative (defensive):** keep the unconditional stash but always drain on master — move `take_completed_worker_run_data()` out of the `need_a_run_streamer` block so the pool is cleared every run regardless, discarding the result when there is no run streamer. The gated-stash version above is cleaner and avoids the wasted allocation/move.


