_Split out from #102 (one issue per bug). Found via an AI-assisted code review with manual verification against commit `5f8ce875`._

`findYamls` treats any argument that merely *contains* `.yaml`/`.yml` as an input file, and `setOptionsValuesFromYamlFile` only catches parse errors, so a missing/mistyped YAML path terminates the process uncaught.

**Affected files**
- `gemc/goptions/goptions.cc:285-295` (`findYamls`)
- `gemc/goptions/goptions.cc:308-319` (`setOptionsValuesFromYamlFile`)
- `gemc/goptions/goptions.cc:122` (file tokens skipped from option parsing)

**Details**

Defect 1 — substring match. `findYamls` classifies a token as a YAML input file when `.yaml`/`.yml` appears *anywhere*:

```cpp
string arg = argv[i];
size_t pos = arg.find(".yaml");
if (pos != string::npos) yaml_files.push_back(arg);
pos = arg.find(".yml");
if (pos != string::npos) yaml_files.push_back(arg);
```

An option value such as `-output_prefix=run.yaml.bak` or `-foo=a.ymlx` is misclassified as an input file. Worse, at line 122 these same tokens are then *skipped* from normal option parsing (`if (find(yaml_files...) != end) continue;`), so the option is silently dropped rather than applied. (A `.yaml` substring that is not a leading-`-` option also passes straight to `YAML::LoadFile`.)

Defect 2 — uncaught `YAML::BadFile`. The loader only catches `ParserException`:

```cpp
try {
    config = YAML::LoadFile(yaml);
}
catch (YAML::ParserException& e) {
    ...
    exit(EC__YAML_PARSING_ERROR);
}
```

`YAML::LoadFile` throws `YAML::BadFile` (a sibling of `ParserException`, both derive from `YAML::Exception`) when the path does not exist or cannot be opened. A mistyped `*.yaml` path therefore escapes the `catch` and calls `std::terminate`.

**Impact**
- Option values containing `.yaml`/`.yml` are silently dropped and fed to the YAML loader instead.
- A typo in a YAML filename crashes with an uncaught exception instead of a clean "file not found" message.

**Proposed fix**

(1) Match a trailing extension instead of a substring:

```diff
 vector<string> GOptions::findYamls(int argc, char* argv[]) {
 	vector<string> yaml_files;
+	auto ends_with = [](const string& s, const string& suffix) {
+		return s.size() >= suffix.size() &&
+		       s.compare(s.size() - suffix.size(), suffix.size(), suffix) == 0;
+	};
 	for (int i = 1; i < argc; i++) {
 		string arg = argv[i];
-		size_t pos = arg.find(".yaml");
-		if (pos != string::npos) yaml_files.push_back(arg);
-		pos = arg.find(".yml");
-		if (pos != string::npos) yaml_files.push_back(arg);
+		if (ends_with(arg, ".yaml") || ends_with(arg, ".yml")) yaml_files.push_back(arg);
 	}
 	return yaml_files;
 }
```

(2) Also catch `YAML::BadFile` (catching the `YAML::Exception` base covers both):

```diff
 	try {
 		config = YAML::LoadFile(yaml);
 	}
+	catch (YAML::BadFile& e) {
+		cerr << FATALERRORL << "Cannot open yaml file " << YELLOWHHL << yaml << RSTHHR
+			<< ". Check the path and spelling." << endl;
+		exit(EC__YAML_PARSING_ERROR);
+	}
 	catch (YAML::ParserException& e) {
 		cerr << FATALERRORL << "Error parsing " << YELLOWHHL << yaml << RSTHHR
 			<< " yaml file." << endl;
```


