_Split out from #102 (one issue per bug). Found via an AI-assisted code review with manual verification against commit `5f8ce875`._

Running `gemc help` with no following topic argument crashes instead of printing help.

**Affected files**
- `gemc/goptions/goptions.cc:102-105`

**Details**
The early help/version handling loop processes the bare `help` token by dereferencing the next argument without a bounds check:

```cpp
else if (strcmp(argv[i], "help") == 0) {
    printOptionOrSwitchHelp(argv[i + 1]);
    exit(EXIT_SUCCESS);
}
```

When `help` is the last token (`gemc help`), `i + 1 == argc`, and `argv[argc]` is the guaranteed-null terminator of the argv array. `printOptionOrSwitchHelp(const std::string& tag)` takes a `std::string`, so the null pointer is passed to the `std::string` constructor, which throws `std::logic_error("basic_string::_M_construct null not valid")` and terminates the program.

**Impact**
`gemc help` (the natural way a user asks for the help index) aborts with an uncaught exception instead of producing useful output. Crash, not just a bad message.

**Proposed fix**
Bounds-check `i + 1 < argc` before reading the next token; if absent, fall back to the general help screen.

```diff
 		else if (strcmp(argv[i], "help") == 0) {
-			printOptionOrSwitchHelp(argv[i + 1]);
-			exit(EXIT_SUCCESS);
+			if (i + 1 < argc) {
+				printOptionOrSwitchHelp(argv[i + 1]);
+			}
+			else {
+				printHelp();
+			}
+			exit(EXIT_SUCCESS);
 		}
```

`printHelp()` already exists in this file and itself calls `exit(EXIT_SUCCESS)`; the trailing `exit` remains for the topic branch.


